\b 2.1. Business Analysis Overview\par
\b0
This chapter presents the business context and concept of operations of the current FF3D game build from the perspective of the implemented product rather than from an earlier design intention. The objective of this chapter is to define why the product exists, what operational problem it addresses, who the relevant stakeholders are, how the current system is used in practice, and what assumptions and constraints shape its deployment.\par

From a software engineering perspective, this chapter is especially important because the project is not a generic entertainment game. It is a simulation-oriented training product with a specific educational purpose. Therefore, the analysis must reflect the actual state of the implemented game loop, the real scene flow, the local persistence model, and the runtime capabilities currently present in the codebase.\par

\b 2.1.1. Problem Statement\par
\b0
Fire prevention and firefighting training often combines classroom teaching, instructor explanation, printed or digital reference material, and periodic hands-on exercises. These methods are valuable because they establish theoretical understanding, safety awareness, and procedural familiarity. However, when considered from the viewpoint of repeatable tactical training, they reveal several structural weaknesses.\par

First, large-scale practical drills are expensive in both time and logistics. A realistic live exercise requires a controlled environment, supporting equipment, supervision, safety coordination, and a limited number of available participants. As a result, such drills cannot always be repeated frequently enough for trainees to practice the same decision pattern multiple times under varied conditions. This limitation affects the learner's ability to develop confidence through repetition.\par

Second, conventional training approaches often separate knowledge acquisition from tactical execution. A trainee may study hazard categories, read standard operating procedures, and watch videos of response actions, but these resources do not necessarily force the learner to make decisions inside a dynamic and time-sensitive environment. In particular, they do not always expose the learner to the uncertainty that characterizes real emergency response, where information is incomplete, time is limited, and decisions have consequences.\par

Third, many digital learning tools focus mainly on the physical action phase of firefighting, such as movement, equipment use, or hazard avoidance. While useful, that focus alone omits an important operational stage: the pre-deployment information gathering process. In a realistic response flow, the quality of the information collected before entering the scene directly affects later decisions. If the responder misunderstands the location of the fire, the possible presence of trapped occupants, or the type of hazard involved, then even strong on-site execution may begin from a flawed tactical foundation.\par

The current FF3D build addresses this gap by integrating information gathering and incident execution into one connected simulation loop. Instead of treating the emergency call as background narrative, the game includes a dedicated Call Phase that influences later mission configuration. The educational value of the system therefore lies not only in action-oriented gameplay, but also in helping the learner understand that early information handling changes later mission conditions.\par

In this sense, the problem addressed by FF3D is not simply the absence of firefighting game content. The deeper problem is the absence of a practical, repeatable, and consequence-aware learning environment that combines pre-deployment judgment with on-site response inside one software product.\par

