\b 2.1.2. Business Objectives\par
\b0
Based on the problem defined above, the business objectives of the current game build are formulated as follows.\par

BO-01 - Provide a repeatable training environment. The system should enable repeated practice without requiring physical drill preparation, thereby lowering the operational cost of replay and experimentation.\par
BO-02 - Cover the complete gameplay training loop. The software should support a coherent flow from scenario preparation, to incident call handling, to on-site execution, and finally to mission result review.\par
BO-03 - Preserve cause-and-effect between phases. Information collected during the Call Phase should influence the incident payload and thereby affect the mission configuration in the on-site scene.\par
BO-04 - Produce measurable feedback. The system should evaluate mission performance through objectives, fail conditions, score, and result presentation so that the learner receives structured feedback instead of only a win or loss state.\par
BO-05 - Support scenario extensibility. The game should be organized around reusable systems so that new scenarios, missions, or data-driven content can be introduced without rebuilding the whole application structure.\par
BO-06 - Support academic and instructional use. The product should be suitable for demonstration, evaluation, and reflective analysis in a learning environment, even if it does not attempt to replace formal real-world certification processes.\par

These objectives align with the current implementation. The codebase already contains a scenario selection flow, a Call Phase module, a payload transfer mechanism, a first-person on-site mission environment, a bot command system, and a mission end review flow. Therefore, the business objectives above are derived from implemented software capability rather than from an unimplemented product vision.\par

\b 2.1.3. Stakeholder Analysis\par
\b0
Stakeholder analysis for the current build must distinguish between the people who are relevant to the project and the users who directly interact with the running software.\par

The first stakeholder group is the student development team. They are responsible for the design, implementation, testing, documentation, and refinement of the system. Their interest lies in producing a stable and academically valid capstone deliverable.\par

The second stakeholder group is the academic supervision and evaluation group, including the project mentor and reviewers. Their interest lies in whether the project demonstrates coherent engineering practice, traceable requirements, an understandable architecture, and a meaningful training-oriented use case.\par

The third stakeholder group is the learner or trainee. This is the most important stakeholder from a product-use perspective. The learner interacts with the game directly and benefits from its training loop, replayability, and feedback system.\par

The fourth stakeholder group includes instructors or training facilitators who may use the product as a teaching support tool. In the current build, this group is a stakeholder rather than an implemented software role. The game does not yet provide instructor dashboards, role-based administration, or remote scenario management features.\par

A critical clarification is required here: the current build does not implement a multi-user operational system with different authenticated permissions. There is no runtime role model such as administrator, dispatcher, reviewer, or training manager inside the software itself. The executable is used locally by one player at a time. Therefore, when discussing stakeholders, the report should not confuse organizational relevance with runtime access control.\par

Table 2.1. Stakeholder analysis and interests\par
Stakeholder | Role in project | Main interest | Relation to current build\par
Development team | Design, implementation, testing, documentation | Deliver a stable and academically valid capstone product | Direct owner of the codebase and deliverables\par
Project mentor / academic reviewers | Supervision and evaluation | Engineering quality, traceability, educational value | External evaluator, not a runtime role\par
Player / trainee | Direct user of the software | Practice decision-making, response flow, and mission execution | Primary runtime user\par
Instructor / facilitator | Uses the product as a teaching support artifact | Demonstration, guided training, review support | Stakeholder only, not implemented as an in-game role\par

\b 2.1.4. Current State vs. Proposed State\par
\b0
In the current state of conventional instruction, important training components are often fragmented. Information gathering may be discussed separately from field movement. Hazard recognition may be explained through static material. Rescue and suppression priorities may be demonstrated in an isolated drill. Performance reflection may depend heavily on instructor observation and memory rather than on a structured digital result record.\par

The proposed state represented by FF3D is an integrated simulation loop in which the learner experiences multiple connected decision stages inside one software session. The player begins by selecting a scenario, moves into the Call Phase, gathers and records information, transitions into an on-site mission that is shaped by the prior phase, and then receives a structured result summary. This integration creates a more coherent learning cycle and allows the same scenario structure to be replayed under controlled conditions.\par

Another important difference is that the proposed state makes causality more visible. Instead of treating early decisions as narrative-only interaction, the game preserves them through payload data that can influence later mission setup. As a result, the learner is not only asked to perform tasks, but also to reflect on how preparation quality affects operational outcome.\par

The proposed state does not replace physical drills or certified practical training. Rather, it functions as an intermediate layer between theory and full live exercise. It is best understood as a simulation-based practice environment that helps reinforce judgment, sequencing, and operational awareness before or between more resource-intensive forms of training.\par

Table 2.2. Current state vs. proposed state\par
Aspect | Current training state | Proposed state in FF3D\par
Repetition | Limited by logistics and drill cost | Repeatable through local replayable software sessions\par
Pre-deployment judgment | Often taught indirectly or separately | Integrated through the Call Phase\par
On-site execution practice | Depends on live drill opportunity | Available through first-person mission scenes\par
Outcome review | Often instructor-dependent | Supported by result, objective, and score presentation\par
Scenario variation | Hard to organize repeatedly | Driven by scenario data and payload-based mission setup\par

\b 2.2. Concept of Operations (ConOps)\par
\b0
The Concept of Operations for FF3D describes how the current game is intended to be used as an implemented software product. This section focuses on runtime behavior, user interaction, scene flow, data transfer, and operational limits as they exist in the present build.\par

\b 2.2.1. System Overview\par
\b0
The current FF3D game is a standalone single-player PC application developed in Unity 6000.x using scene-based progression and feature-based module organization. The system is intended to simulate a training-oriented emergency response loop in which the player performs both pre-deployment information handling and on-site mission execution.\par

At a high level, the current gameplay loop can be described as follows:\par

Main Menu -> Loading Scene -> Level Select -> Call Phase -> On-site Mission Scene -> Mission Result / End Review.\par

The process begins in the Main Menu, where the player can create or continue a local profile. The Loading Scene acts as a controlled transition stage between scene changes. From there, the player enters the Level Select module and chooses a level and a scenario. The chosen scenario determines which Call Phase scenario data will be loaded and which on-site scene will eventually be used.\par

Inside the Call Phase, the player interacts with transcript-driven and report-driven interfaces to collect incident information, choose follow-up questions, extract key details, and perform risk assessment. When the player completes this phase, the system generates structured cross-scene data in the form of a call-phase result snapshot and an IncidentWorldSetupPayload.\par

The IncidentWorldSetupPayload is a central operational data object in the current build. It contains scenario and mission configuration data such as case identifier, scenario identifier, fire origin, logical fire location, hazard-related values, smoke-related values, severity band, trapped-person estimate, confidence score, and a report snapshot. This payload is then persisted through the loading-flow system and consumed by the on-site setup logic.\par

After the transition, the player enters an on-site mission scene. In that environment, the system switches from information handling to first-person incident response. The player can move through the scene, interact with doors and windows, manage equipment, respond to hazards, rescue victims, and issue orders to AI-controlled bot teammates. The mission system evaluates objectives, fail conditions, timing, and score while the player is active in the scene.\par

When the mission reaches a completed or failed state, the game presents a result-oriented review interface. This stage provides mission outcome information, scoring context, and local progression handling where applicable. From a ConOps perspective, this closes the training loop and prepares the player either to continue, replay, or return to the broader menu flow.\par

It is important to note that the current build does not expose every internal step as a visible player-facing phase. For example, payload generation and deterministic seed resolution are core internal mechanisms, but they are not separate user-facing scenes. Therefore, the operational description must distinguish between visible stages in the player journey and invisible system services that support those stages.\par

