\b 2.2.2. User Roles and Permissions\par
\b0
The current runtime system should be modeled with one direct user role only: the player.\par

The player is responsible for launching the application, selecting or continuing a local profile, choosing a level and scenario, completing the Call Phase, entering the on-site mission, managing equipment and actions, issuing commands to bots, and reviewing mission results. This role is both the primary user role and the central pedagogical focus of the product.\par

No other formal software role is currently implemented in the runtime application. There is no login model, no instructor console, no administrator dashboard, no remote review workflow, and no network-based session control. The game therefore does not contain a role-based permission system in the conventional software sense.\par

This distinction matters because educational stakeholders may still refer to roles such as instructor, evaluator, or training supervisor. Those labels are meaningful in a broader training context, but they should not be described as implemented in-game roles unless future versions of the software actually provide different role-specific access paths.\par

The current build is therefore best documented as follows:\par

Player: the only direct runtime role.\par
Instructor / Evaluator: external stakeholder role, not an in-game permission role.\par
Development Team / Maintainer: project-level stakeholder role, not part of runtime gameplay.\par

Table 2.3. Runtime role model and stakeholder boundary\par
Category | Name | Implemented in runtime | Notes\par
Runtime role | Player | Yes | The only direct software user during normal gameplay\par
Stakeholder | Instructor / evaluator | No | May use the product for teaching or assessment, but not as a runtime role\par
Stakeholder | Development / QA reviewer | No | Relevant to engineering workflow, not normal gameplay flow\par
System role | Administrator / dispatcher / remote reviewer | No | Not implemented in the current build\par

\b 2.2.3. Operational Environment\par
\b0
The current game operates as an offline desktop application intended for PC use. It relies on local Unity assets, local scene transitions, and local persistence mechanisms such as PlayerPrefs and profile storage. The product is designed for keyboard-and-mouse interaction in a first-person environment and assumes a standard Windows-based academic or personal computer environment.\par

From a software deployment perspective, the game uses local Unity scenes and local runtime assets. The main enabled scenes in the current build configuration include Boot Intro, Main Menu, Loading Scene, Level Select, Tutorial, Call Phase, Map1, and Map3. These scenes represent the current operational envelope of the product. Other scenes or experimental content in the repository should not automatically be interpreted as active production flow unless they are explicitly enabled or integrated into the main scene sequence.\par

The platform assumptions of the operational environment are conservative. The current build is designed for a desktop environment, with no implementation of cloud synchronization, external data services, or online multiplayer support. The system does not require internet connectivity to execute its primary loop. Session state and progression data are handled locally.\par

The operational environment also includes runtime feature modules such as UI systems, mission systems, equipment systems, minimap systems, bot command systems, and payload-driven setup systems. These operate together inside the Unity process, but they do not rely on a separate backend service layer.\par

In documentation terms, this means that FF3D should be described as a self-contained simulation product rather than a distributed training platform.\par

