\b 2.2.4. Operational Scenarios\par
\b0
The following operational scenarios describe how the current game is used in practice. These scenarios are rewritten to match the implemented build and should not assume unverified design features.\par

\b Scenario 1: Standard End-to-End Training Session\par
\b0
Context: A player starts a normal training session using the current main gameplay loop.\par

Flow:\par
The player launches the application and reaches the Main Menu.\par
The player creates a new local profile or continues an existing one.\par
The system transitions through the Loading Scene into Level Select.\par
The player chooses a level and scenario from the available selection interface.\par
The system opens the corresponding Call Phase scenario.\par
During the Call Phase, the player reads transcript content, selects or confirms relevant details, asks follow-up questions, completes incident reporting fields, and performs risk assessment.\par
The system generates a call-phase result snapshot and an incident payload for the next scene.\par
The player is routed into the corresponding on-site mission scene.\par
The mission runs until success or failure conditions are reached.\par
The player reviews the mission result interface and may continue the larger progress loop from there.\par

Outcome: The player completes one full software-supported learning cycle from scenario preparation to post-mission feedback.\par

[Insert Figure 2.3. Scenario 1 operational flow]\par

\b Scenario 2: Coordinated Response with AI Bot Support\par
\b0
Context: A player enters an on-site mission that includes AI bot agents capable of receiving commands.\par

Flow:\par
The player assesses the scene and identifies operational needs such as movement, suppression, rescue, breach, or hazard isolation.\par
The player uses the bot command system to select a commandable bot and issue a context-appropriate order.\par
Depending on the situation, the player may command bots to move, extinguish, follow, rescue, hold, breach, isolate, or regroup.\par
Bots perform their assigned behavior using their own execution logic, navigation, and interaction systems.\par
The player continues contributing directly inside the mission while also coordinating bot actions as part of incident management.\par

Outcome: The player practices distributed task execution and command-oriented thinking rather than completing every task manually.\par

[Insert Figure 2.4. Scenario 2 bot coordination flow]\par

\b Scenario 3: Hazard Recognition and Environmental Adaptation\par
\b0
Context: A player encounters an on-site mission in which smoke, fire spread, and hazard-related factors influence movement and decision-making.\par

Flow:\par
The player enters the mission scene that has been configured by the transferred incident payload.\par
The player observes environmental conditions such as active fire, restricted visibility, smoke accumulation, and risk-related scene context.\par
The player chooses appropriate tools and protective equipment when available.\par
The player may interact with environmental elements such as windows, doors, and mission objects to gain access, reduce obstacles, or improve survivability.\par
The mission system evaluates the consequences of these actions through objective progress, fail conditions, and scoring.\par

Outcome: The player learns to adapt actions to environmental risk rather than treating the mission as a simple linear action sequence.\par

[Insert Figure 2.5. Scenario 3 environmental hazard flow]\par

\b Scenario 4: Victim Rescue and Safe-Zone Delivery\par
\b0
Context: A player performs rescue tasks involving victim condition, movement, and delivery objectives.\par

Flow:\par
The player locates one or more victims inside the mission environment.\par
The player uses the available interaction flow to engage with the victim according to the victim's state and the current rescue context.\par
The player may stabilize, carry, or otherwise handle the rescue target depending on scene configuration and available systems.\par
The player then delivers the rescued target to a designated safe zone or rescue completion area recognized by the mission logic.\par
The mission system updates progress accordingly and incorporates the rescue outcome into the final mission result.\par

Outcome: The player practices rescue prioritization and victim handling as an integral part of the mission rather than as a separate mini-game.\par

[Insert Figure 2.6. Scenario 4 rescue flow]\par

\b Scenario 5: Result Review and Progress Continuation\par
\b0
Context: A player reaches the end of a mission and uses result information to continue training.\par

Flow:\par
After the mission reaches a completed or failed state, the result-oriented overlay and review interface becomes available.\par
The player reviews objective status, score-related information, and completion outcome.\par
Where applicable, the system persists completion-related data to the player's local progress record.\par
The player may then return to the broader menu flow, continue progression, or begin another scenario.\par

Outcome: The product supports iterative training through local progression and repeatable feedback.\par

[Insert Figure 2.7. Scenario 5 result review flow]\par

\b 2.2.5. System Interfaces\par
\b0
The current FF3D build is primarily defined by internal runtime interfaces rather than external enterprise integrations. The most relevant interfaces are described below.\par

User interaction interface: This includes keyboard-and-mouse control for movement, camera direction, interaction, inventory usage, equipment handling, command issuing, minimap behavior, and dispatch-note related interaction.\par

Scenario selection interface: The Level Select system allows the player to choose a level and scenario. It maps that selection into the loading-flow state so the next scene can be prepared correctly.\par

Call Phase interface: This consists of transcript presentation, follow-up question selection, extraction and report entry components, and risk assessment components. Together, these interfaces capture the pre-deployment part of the training loop.\par

Cross-scene state interface: The LoadingFlowState service acts as a local transfer mechanism for pending target scene information, scenario resource paths, case identifiers, pending on-site scene name, call-phase result snapshot, and IncidentWorldSetupPayload.\par

On-site gameplay interface: Inside the mission scene, the player interacts with the mission system, interaction system, inventory system, equipment systems, bot command system, minimap system, and HUD system.\par

Persistence interface: The current build stores profile and progress data locally. Player profile continuation and mission completion recording are part of the implemented runtime behavior.\par

Notably absent interfaces include external authentication, cloud synchronization, remote telemetry transmission, multiplayer networking, and external dispatch integration. These are outside the current operational scope.\par

Table 2.5. Implemented system interfaces\par
Interface | Purpose | Implemented through\par
Menu and profile interface | Create or continue local progress | MainMenuScript, PlayerProgressProfileStore\par
Scenario selection interface | Choose level and scenario | LevelSelectSceneController, LevelScenarioCatalog\par
Call Phase interface | Gather and report incident information | Transcript UI, IncidentReportController, AssessRisk flow\par
Cross-scene flow interface | Transfer pending scene and mission data | LoadingFlowState\par
On-site gameplay interface | Execute mission actions and interactions | FPSInteractionSystem, FPSInventorySystem, IncidentMissionSystem\par
Bot command interface | Command AI teammates | FPSCommandSystem, BotCommandAgent\par
Review interface | Display mission result and completion data | MissionEndOverlayController and related UI\par

\b 2.2.6. Constraints and Assumptions\par
\b0
The concept of operations of the current build is shaped by several practical constraints and assumptions.\par

Constraints:\par
C-01: The current build is scoped as a single-player desktop game and should not be documented as a multiplayer, cloud-based, or institution-wide distributed platform.\par
C-02: The software operates offline and uses local persistence mechanisms only.\par
C-03: The number of production-ready scenarios and content variations is limited by capstone scope, development time, and scene authoring effort.\par
C-04: Runtime behavior depends on Unity scene wiring, local assets, and ScriptableObject-driven data definitions.\par
C-05: Some repository content remains experimental, incomplete, or work in progress and should not automatically be treated as core production functionality.\par

Assumptions:\par
A-01: Players possess basic PC interaction literacy, including keyboard movement and mouse-based camera navigation.\par
A-02: The game is used as a simulation-based instructional tool and not as a replacement for formal certification or live operational qualification.\par
A-03: Mission evaluation is based on in-game objectives, fail conditions, and scoring logic, which are software-defined and not equivalent to official operational assessment standards.\par
A-04: Scenario execution depends on local configuration and pre-authored content rather than live data from external emergency systems.\par
A-05: The player accepts a simplified simulation abstraction in which training value comes from structured decision flow and repeatability, not from full real-world procedural completeness.\par

